<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1972-03-23T10:50:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1972-03-23T10:50:00-05:00" n="241" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d241">
                        <head>241. Telegram 3666 From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in
                                India</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                                State</gloss><note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d241fn1">Source:
                                National Archives, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central
                                Files 1970–73, DEF 15 <gloss target="#t_PAK1">PAK</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>. Top Secret; <gloss target="#t_Exdis1">Exdis</gloss>.</note>
                            <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d241fn2">Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_KKB1">Keating</persName> expressed his opposition to
                                any increase in U.S. military collaboration with Pakistan.</note>
                        </head>
                        <dateline><placeName>New Delhi</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1972-03-23T15:50:00+00:00">March 23, 1972, 1550Z</date>
                        </dateline>
                        <list type="subject">
                            <head>Subject:</head>
                            <item>
                                <gloss target="#t_GOP1">GOP</gloss> Offer of Military Facilities in
                                Pakistan</item>
                        </list>
                        <list type="references">
                            <head>REF:</head>
                            <item>A) State 49598</item>
                            <item>B) Islamabad 2213</item>
                            <item>C) Islamabad 2247</item>
                        </list>
                        <p>1. Apparent <gloss target="#t_GOP1">GOP</gloss> decision to seek replay
                            history of substantial <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss> military supply
                            and collaboration against India strikes me as ominously irrational and,
                            if pursued, certain to prejudice prospects for durable peace in South
                            Asia.</p>
                        <p>2. I hope this Embassy will re consulted before any serious consideration
                            is given to the proposals contained reftels.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_KKB1">Keating</persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>